+# Exploration 002 Summary
+
+## Goal
+
+Run the recursive exact closure audit on each canonical one-triad first-budget
+seed.
+
+## What I Tried
+
+- Started from the canonical seed catalog from Exploration 001.
+- Applied the frozen Step-1 closure rule in order:
+  conjugate completion first,
+  then every ordered pair on the full active ledger,
+  then every nonzero forced target mode with its conjugate completion.
+- Checked explicitly which pairs stay on the original orbit and which pairs
+  created by mirror completion force new wavevectors.
+
+## Outcome
+
+`succeeded`
+
+## One Key Takeaway
+
+No honest first-budget seed survives.
+Once the one-triad seed is mirror-completed, off-orbit active pairs such as
+`(p, -q)`, `(k, p)`, and `(k, q)` force new wavevectors
+`p - q`, `2p + q`, and `p + 2q`, so every canonical sign-sheet class dies by
+the same current-budget obstruction:
+recursive closure spills beyond the one-triad budget on the first honest pass.
+
+## Leads Worth Pursuing
+
+- Treat Step 3 as unearned at this budget unless an admissible enlargement
+  somehow restores a genuinely finite exact survivor.
+- Use the enlargement pass only to confirm that the visually tidy mirror-complete
+  triad is an over-pruned pseudo-survivor, not a real closed support.
+
+## Unexpected Findings
+
+- The decisive spill does not require a full sign-by-sign coefficient table:
+  the frozen closure rule plus nondegenerate one-triad geometry already force
+  new wavevectors.
+- Self-pairs are not the issue; the real spill comes from distinct off-orbit
+  pairs created by mandatory conjugate completion.
