+# Exploration 003 Summary
+
+## Goal
+
+Run the required admissible-enlargement audit on any apparent first-budget
+survivor, or package a clean current-budget negative if no honest survivor
+remains.
+
+## What I Tried
+
+- Took the closure result from Exploration 002 as input.
+- Identified the only tempting pseudo-survivor:
+  the mirror-complete one-triad sheet `±p, ±q, ±k` obtained by stopping too
+  early.
+- Applied the frozen admissible enlargement rule by adding the first
+  shared-mode exact triad orbit on `p - q` and rerunning closure from scratch.
+
+## Outcome
+
+`succeeded`
+
+## One Key Takeaway
+
+The enlargement audit confirms the negative.
+Adding the first forced shared-mode orbit on `p - q` immediately forces further
+new modes such as `2p - q`, `-2q`, `2p`, and `p + 2q`, so the tidy
+mirror-complete one-triad picture is only a pseudo-survivor created by
+over-pruning.
+No genuinely invariant finite support survives the first budget, and Chain
+Step 3 is not earned on this rung.
+
+## Leads Worth Pursuing
+
+- Present this as a controller-facing first-budget obstruction memo, not as a
+  global failure of the mission.
+- If controller authorizes escalation, move only to the next declared budget,
+  not to dynamics on the current one.
+
+## Unexpected Findings
+
+- The enlargement audit did not weaken the clean negative; it sharpened it by
+  showing that even the most tempting visually closed seed is not stable under
+  the branch's own admissible-enlargement policy.
