+## Apparent Survivor To Audit
+
+- `[INFERRED]` Exploration 002 leaves **no honest survivor** after the frozen
+  recursive-closure rule is applied.
+- `[INFERRED]` The only cosmetically tempting pseudo-survivor is the
+  mirror-complete six-wavevector sheet
+
+  ```text
+  S_pseudo = { ±p, ±q, ±k },
+  k = p + q,
+  ```
+
+  on one canonical sign sheet, obtained by stopping after conjugate completion
+  and the orbit-internal pairs.
+- `[VERIFIED]` That pseudo-survivor is already invalid as an exact fixed point
+  because Exploration 002 showed that the same ledger also contains off-orbit
+  pairs like `(p, -q)`, `(k, p)`, and `(k, q)`.
+
+## Admissible Enlargement Audit
+
+### Enlargement used
+
+- `[INFERRED]` Use Step-1 enlargement rule 2:
+  add one complete exact triad orbit sharing at least one mode with the current
+  support, together with the symmetry partners required by conjugation and
+  triad relabeling, and then rerun closure from scratch.
+- `[INFERRED]` The most natural shared-mode enlargement is the first forced
+  orbit already exposed by Exploration 002:
+
+  ```text
+  (p - q, p, -q)
+  ```
+
+  with one live target helicity sector on `p - q` and the corresponding mirror
+  partners.
+
+### Reclosed enlarged ledger
+
+- `[INFERRED]` After adding the shared-mode orbit on
+  `r := p - q`,
+  the enlarged active wavevector ledger contains
+
+  ```text
+  { ±p, ±q, ±k, ±r }.
+  ```
+
+- `[INFERRED]` Rerunning the same closure rule from scratch now forces further
+  off-orbit pairs, for example:
+
+  ```text
+  (r, p)   -> 2p - q,
+  (r, -k)  -> -2q,
+  (r, k)   -> 2p,
+  (k, q)   -> p + 2q.
+  ```
+
+- `[INFERRED]` These are again outside the one-triad budget and outside the
